South Hamilton
Bus/Transportation Rules/Guidelines for 2020-2021

All bus drivers MUST wear a mask or face covering from the time he/she enters until his/her departures the bus.

All students/passengers MUST wear a mask or face covering from the time he/she enters until his/her departures the bus.

All students will be assigned a seat for the entire semester and MUST not move from or interact (turn around, etc.) with others on the bus during the entire trip.

Students MUST not stand or put him/herself in the aisle while the bus is moving.

Student passengers will be dismissed front to back.

***The district is working to prevent the spread of COVID-19 and has determined the rules above are necessary to limit person-to-person infection. Do know the district will expect all passengers to follow these rules --- and the consequences for passengers not following the district’s expectations will include suspension, up to exclusion from district transportation.

Orientation will be held next Wednesday, August 19th, and Thursday, August 20th, from 5:00-6:00 pm.

Signs posted at entrances state, “if no face mask, NO entrance” --- the district assumes all individuals will abide by this expectation to better ensure the health and safety of others is achieved
--
Dr. Ken Howard, Ed.D.

post_text:
To: All South Hamilton Stakeholders

From: Dr. Ken Howard

Re: Return to Play - Baseball and Softball

The district continues to work with federal, state and local authorities to determine if the multiple health and safety requirements set forth by the CDC, public health, the Iowa Department of Education, and the athletic association/union. We believe the needed information has been collected, a drafted plan created, and a final decision as to participation will be made within the next couple of days. I do ask that individuals are patient – as one can be – for this is an extreme situation that none of us have ever been in, and the district desires to be thoughtful and well-prepared so that our students, staff, and patrons are as safe as possible.--

Governor Reynolds announced a return to play for high school summer sports, and the IHSAA and IGHSAU adopted this guidance. Along with June 1 return to practices at school facilities, the IHSAA and IGHSAU have also set forth some other specifications for schools.

On Thursday, May 21 the South Hamilton administration and coaches will be meeting to see if our school can meet these specifications. Following this meeting, the administration will communicate with the School Board to finalize our plans.

Once a plan is in place we will communicate out to students, parents, and stakeholders. Thank you, and GO HAWKS!

post_text:
The district's expanded Leadership Team will formally meet today to begin the creation of the South Hamilton Return to Learn plan as required by the Iowa Department of Education. This plan will be extensive, specific, and flexible so that the district is able to provide our students with high-quality learning opportunities while best ensuring the health and safety of all our stakeholders.

We do know the plan will include options that will range from virtual instruction and hybrid learning to a return to on-site learning. South Hamilton, like all districts across Iowa, will focus on virtual options initially, with the hope the other educational delivery service types may be utilized, if and when, conditions improve per the fight against the Coronavirus.

The district will keep all informed as to the plan's progress.

Be safe and healthy,

Dr. Howard

**SH Greenhouse Plant Sale Update**

We are still having our spring plant sale! Starting Monday April 27th, all of the plants raised by the SH Greenhouse Management Class will be for sale at the Jewell Farm and Home Store during their normal store hours for the next couple weeks!

We are very thankful that The Jewell Farm and Home Store has stepped up to support our students and our program! Couldn’t have done it without them!

The kids worked really hard this winter/spring to put on a good plant sale and Mr. Ness did everything he could to not screw that up during this extended Covid Break!

Would really appreciate your support!!

Plugs - $1.00
3.5 Inch Pots - $2.00
Hanging Baskets -$15.00

Plants for sale:
Wave Petunias
Geraniums
Coleus
Impatiens
Begonias
Marigolds
Tomatoes
Peppers

Sweet Potato Vine

post_text:
Pick up Day / Student Items

Elementary Parents,

We have scheduled Wednesday, April 29th for you to pick up any student items left in the classroom. Your child’s teacher will have items bagged up and ready to be picked up from 12:00 – 6:00 pm on the 29th. Please pull in the drive on the south parking lot by the flagpole. Preschool – 4th grade bags will be picked up at the south door, 5/6 items and band instruments will be picked up in front of the 5/6 door. We will have staff at those locations to get your child’s bag. Please stay in your car, we will bring it to you.

If you need to look through the Lost and Found, please pull in the bus drive. Lost and found items will be displayed outside the East entrance door by the office. Only 1 family at a time is allowed. Please stay in your car until it is your family’s turn.

The nurse will be available to distribute any medications that need to go home for the year.

Thank you for your cooperation.

Paul Hemphill

The nurse will be available to distribute any medications that need to go home for the year.

Thank you for your cooperation.

Paul Hemphill

More information pertaining to any changes in processes, plans and annually scheduled events will be shared in the coming days.

Be safe and learn well.

- Dr. Howard

I was talking to someone today and we both decided there is one thing we are truly missing during this time...voices. The voices of South Hamilton students in the hallways, classrooms, gym, and playgrounds. We can provide high-quality virtual educational opportunities, but the voices we have come to treasure on our campus are silent. When the voices return --- South Hamilton will be back! Hopefully soon.

Dr. Howard

post_text:
The parade will start in Jewell at the MS/HS building at 1:00 pm, Wednesday, April 8th. We will follow this route around each town as pictured. We would like the students to come outside and wave at us as we drive by. We are looking forward to seeing everyone!

Directions:

From the MS/HS circle drive, south on Division St, Meadowlake, Lakeview, Fountain, back to Division St (north), Park, East Lane, Anderson, Blaine, Edwards, (north on) Main, Carmichael, 2nd St, Lyon, then out of town on D56 toward Stanhope.

Arrive in Stanhope at 1:24 pm, turn east on Center St, School, Iowa, Kepler, Main, Howard, Railway, Parker, and then south on Hwy 17, east on 175 to Hwy 69, turn south toward Randall.

Arrive in Randall at 1:45 pm. Turn south on 1st St, Main, Long St east out of town. Turn north at R61 towards Ellsworth.

Arrive in Ellsworth at 1:55 pm. Turn east on Elmo St, Dewitt, Dubuque, Dayton, Park, DeSota, Park, Delphi then west out of town on 175. End of parade.

The South Hamilton Leadership met today to review and further plans for a potentially lengthy closure. The administrative group is waiting for Governor Kim Reynolds to speak this afternoon at 4:30 p.m. before finalizing said plans.

All South Hamilton buildings are now inaccessible except for designated staff. All athletic practices and activities are canceled effective immediately. Please do not call the schools now, we ask individuals to wait for the district’s official statement pertaining to the COVID-19 situation.

post_text:
Local author Sarah Binder visited South Hamilton Elementary to share her first published book "Dreaming of a White Christmas." Mrs. Binder talked about the writing and publishing process, and shared samples of the illustrator's work while explaining how pictures are created for a book. It was fun listening to Sarah read her book aloud. It is truly a story of the magic and wonder of Christmas.

Thank you, Sarah, for also donating a signed copy of your book to our library. It will be enjoyed for many years to come! We look forward to reading your next book.

post_text:
The butterfly release has begun! Second and third graders released their first butterflies with delight and a little disappointment after being so involved in their first "citizen science" project. Each butterfly is tagged as part of the Monarch Watch program. If you discover a monarch with a tag on its wing, you can contact MWTAG.org to submit the recovery information so they can track the migration of the monarchs to Mexico.

Students in 1st-4th grade have had a great time participating in the Monarch Egg Project since school started this fall. Thank you to Hamilton County Extension and Leah Feltz, the Extension Outreach Educator for bringing this experience to our students. Hamilton County Extension

post_text:
Monarchs on the Move! -- 2019 Monarch Eggs Project

This project is supported by the USDA-ARS Unit on the Iowa State University campus, where they maintain a Monarch butterfly colony all year long. For this project, monarch eggs are provided to educators so that every student in the classroom can rear a monarch butterfly from egg, caterpillar, chrysalis, to adult. This project starts at the beginning of the school year. Since it takes a month to develop from egg to adult butterfly, the timing is perfect for the reared butterflies to hopefully join the fall migration to Mexico. The Monarch Egg Project is funded by an Iowa DNR REAP-CEP grant.

Students in Grades 1-4 started their year with this project. They are supported by Leah Feltz, Hamilton County K-12 Outreach Educator, Iowa State University Extension.

In our Nation's Capital, students visited the White House, Library of Congress, many monuments and memorials, the Holocaust Memorial Museum, Mount Vernon, and three of the Smithsonian museums (to name a few). The group posed for a photo after meeting Senator Chuck Grassley on the stairs of the capital building.

Students took a moment on Tuesday afternoon to honor their Elementary Reading Volunteers and recognize the impact of their efforts all year round.

The time reading volunteers spend with new readers encouraging their skills and promoting a love for reading makes a difference. Reading books with children and listening to children read aloud is a great way to help support the next generation of readers. We thank you for your support throughout the year.

If you know of others who might be interested in becoming a reading volunteer, or for more information about the volunteer program, contact South Hamilton Elementary.

Mrs. Voga’s Current Affairs Class and Mr. Wintermote’s TV/Media Class took a field trip to IHeartMedia in Des Moines. While there, the students were able to tour the facilities which house the radio stations of 1040 WHO, 1460 KXNO, 100.3 The Bus, KISS 107.5, and Alt 106.3.

The students were able to see the studios of the different stations and the newsroom. They got to visit with a few of the radio personalities and watch while a live show was on the air. It was a great tour and the students learned a lot about the radio business and radio broadcasting as a career.

post_text: The sixth graders participated in an exciting Junior Achievement program called JA BizTown. JA Biz- Town encompasses important elements of community and economy, work readiness, financial literacy, and business management. As part of the program, they spent the day today at the JA BizTown site in Des Moines. This on-site visit provided students with an opportunity to apply what they have learned in a realistic setting. Each student assumed a job, produced and/or sold products, received a paycheck, worked on a business team, repaid business loans, shopped, and managed a personal bank account. Throughout the program, students were encouraged to use critical thinking skills to learn about key economic concepts as they explored and enhanced their understanding of free enterprise. Thank you to Mr. Klemp and the Parent Volunteers for making this learning experience a huge success!!!
